☁️ Cloud Service Models

Cloud computing provides services in three primary models:

IaaS
PaaS
SaaS
1. IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service)
Definition

IaaS provides virtualized computing resources over the internet.

The cloud provider manages:

Physical servers
Storage
Networking
Virtualization

The customer manages:

Operating System
Applications
Data
Examples
Amazon EC2
Microsoft Azure Virtual Machines
Google Compute Engine
Use Cases
Hosting applications
Virtual servers
Disaster recovery
Development environments
2. PaaS (Platform as a Service)
Definition

PaaS provides a platform for developing, testing, and deploying applications without managing the underlying infrastructure.

The cloud provider manages:

Infrastructure
Operating System
Runtime
Middleware

The customer manages:

Application code
Data
Examples
Google App Engine
Azure App Service
Heroku
Benefits
Faster application development
No server management
Automatic scaling
3. SaaS (Software as a Service)
Definition

SaaS delivers fully functional software applications over the internet.

The cloud provider manages everything.

Users simply access the software through a web browser.

Examples
Gmail
Microsoft 365
Salesforce
Zoom
Benefits
No installation required
Accessible from anywhere
Automatic updates
Difference Between IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS
Feature	IaaS	PaaS	SaaS
Infrastructure Managed By	Cloud Provider	Cloud Provider	Cloud Provider
Operating System Managed By	Customer	Cloud Provider	Cloud Provider
Application Managed By	Customer	Customer	Cloud Provider
User Responsibility	OS, Apps, Data	Apps, Data	Only use the software
Example	Amazon EC2	Google App Engine	Gmail
📊 Observability Tools
What is Observability?

Observability is the ability to understand the internal state of an application or system by analyzing its outputs.

The three pillars of observability are:

Logs
Metrics
Traces
1. Logs

Logs are detailed records of events that occur within an application or system.

Example
2026-06-30 10:30:45 INFO User login successful
2026-06-30 10:31:10 ERROR Database connection failed
Uses
Troubleshooting
Debugging
Security auditing
2. Metrics

Metrics are numerical values collected over time that represent system performance.

Examples
CPU Usage
Memory Usage
Disk Usage
Network Traffic
Response Time
Uses
Performance monitoring
Capacity planning
Alerting
3. Traces

Traces show the complete journey of a request through multiple services.

Example
Client
   │
API Gateway
   │
Authentication Service
   │
Order Service
   │
Database

Traces help identify where delays or failures occur.

Uses
Performance optimization
Root cause analysis
Microservices debugging
🖥️ Application Monitoring
Definition

Application monitoring tracks the health, availability, and performance of software applications.

Monitors
Response time
API performance
Error rates
Request throughput
Application availability
Example

An e-commerce application is monitored to ensure users can place orders without delays.

Benefits
Detects application failures
Improves user experience
Helps identify slow APIs
🏗️ Infrastructure Monitoring
Definition

Infrastructure monitoring tracks the health and performance of the underlying hardware and cloud resources.

Monitors
CPU Usage
Memory Usage
Disk Usage
Network Utilization
Server Health
Example

A cloud administrator monitors CPU usage on virtual machines to prevent performance issues.

Benefits
Prevents server failures
Improves resource utilization
Ensures high availability
Difference Between Application Monitoring and Infrastructure Monitoring
Application Monitoring	Infrastructure Monitoring
Focuses on software performance	Focuses on hardware and infrastructure
Monitors APIs, response time, errors	Monitors CPU, memory, disk, and network
Helps improve user experience	Helps maintain system health
